div.p:
A young Girle of between 14 and 15 years of age, being purued by her Mother, who would needs beat her, throws her elf into the arms of one, who was a Brother of a certain Community of Workmen, etablihed in a part of the Town, that it is not neceary to name;


this Man conducts her to his Chamber, and forces her; he preently communicates the opportunity to him that uually lay with him, who failed not to make ue of the occaion, and to dicover it alo to another of his Camerades; in o much that in three days he was there, ix everal perons made ue of her. After this, the wiet among them, foreeeing that this buines was like to draw ome dangerous conequence, ent her home again by a Woman, that feigned to have found her in a Church; her Mother preently huts her up in a Cloet, wherein no body was uffer'd to enter but her elf, and ix days afterwards he complain'd of great pains that he uffered when he made Urine; her Mother caued her to be viited, and was told that he had got a Clap; nevertheles they neglected to make ue of any Cure, becaue they would not believe it, and twelve days afterwards there appeared a Bubo in her right Groin: then they began to quetion her about it, and he accued the perons he had been with; they were all viited by Order of Jutice, and were all found clean, and in good health; And the Chirurgeon that imparted


to me this tory, aured me that he had familiarly frequented their Company a long time afterwards, and that he had never found any Venereal Ditemper among any of them, though 'tis now twelve years ince it hapned.

This new way of judging of Dieaes, will urely very much urprize all thoe that hall make ome reflections on the difficulty there is of knowing them, and chiefly thoe Dieaes whoe caues are abconded in the ecret internal parts, uch as is the univeral Pox; ince the difficulty of knowing them is ometimes o great, that the mot expert, profound, and mot knowing Phyicians, do happen to be mitaken, in taking one for another;


and they do oberve for this purpoe, the common Rule of Lawyers, by which they do never offer to give determinate Judgment, upon the preence of one Witnes only. But beides thee coniderations, it mut alo be remarked by the by, that thoe words of Fine Pox, do how at the ame time both the ignorance, and quacking of thoe who make ue of them: But after all, this ame Patient was a little afterwards comforted again by one that proved more honet, who after an ample knowledge of the circumtances I related, gave the ame Name to this Dieae that I had done before, and o advied him to thoe Remedies that I had propoed to him, by the ue of which Remedies he was quite cured in a hort time. Moreover it may be aid, that Interet was the ole Motive of this treacherous dealing; for there is no likelihood that the ambition of appearing a great Doctor, hould have been the caue, ince he might have appeared o much more by reaoning on the Dieae, than pronouncing uch fine words. Nor is there any reaon to believe he did it to render me a good Office, ince Offices of o high a nature are but eldom done without


the hopes of receiving equal ones again, and we two were not of Intelligence enough for that. Therefore it is much more likely, he thought with himelf that I deired to put this peron under his hands, for ome particular conideration, and o he might have no other thought but of embracing the occaion offered.
